You mentioned that you are waiting for social media to start accepting photos like the ones that you can create using "Virtual Spot."  Actually, there is a way to use an image like that online right now. You see, the way that "Virtual Spot" works, is that it captures an entire series of images of whatever you are photographing<including yourself>. It does so by taking one still frame after another in sequence. These can be downloaded into your computer. The way that you can use these in social media, is to take your "Virtual Spot" images and convert them into an "Animated Gif." Essentially, what you are doing with those "Virtual Spot" images, is converting them to a short video, which is exactly what an "Animated Gif" actually is. Gif images are used online quite extensively and are created to play in loops, over and over.

There are a host of "Gif Maker" software available online for downloading. Some higher end ones must be paid for, but there are quite a few available for free download and unlimited use. Once you create a "Gif" image, it can be safely uploaded online and posted wherever you want, including on social media.  It's only a simple matter of uploading a video. The gif can be configured to play automatically when selected. I just wanted to point that out so that you don't need to wait for specialty software for using "Virtual Spot" images.  Hope this helps, and good luck. Totally adorbs!‚Äù 
Then him clacking the mouse as he goes to leave??', 'How many views?', 'The clock is ticking. Tick Tock Tick Tock.', 'I'm a 1991 baby, but I vaguely remember this thing. That packaging actually feels nostalgic. I might've had a chance to try one when I was little.

I was just 2 when I was exposed to computers. An IBM DOS PC running on MS-DOS 6 with a fancy skin called "Windows 3.1" was my first PC. Can't believe it's 3 decades ago. The '90s and 2000s don't feel that distant for some reason.', 'GREEN SCREEN KID', 'Love Bill Nye!', '5:00 it turned to a veritasium videoüòÖ', 'I have the Macintosh boot up sound stuck in my memory, is that normal', '2:38 woweee', '2:24 beige‚Ä¶?', 'nice show', 'Can I put a $50 wallpaper on it?', 'iLOVEaPPLEcOMPUTERS tHANKs 4 the video mARQues üòÄ', 'his face while watching as the people said the floppy disks would make good coasters was funny', 'What about the tape?', "Fun general overview, some good memories here too. I never worked with the 128k, but I programmed on the Apple II line extensively. One of the major challenges I faced as a developer working with the Apple II was the lack of good C compilers. Since the 6502 processor was more suited for assembly language, I ended up spending hours learning and writing assembly code just to get my projects moving forward. I often wrote small sections of code in assembly and then hand-optimized them to fit into the quirky memory architecture. I even designed my own makeshift stack management system to handle the hardware limitations, though it was more of a patchwork solution than something elegant.

In one particular project, I was trying to implement a small game, and the limited stack space nearly drove me crazy. I ended up breaking down complex functions into smaller subroutines just to avoid running out of stack memory. It was a frustrating but invaluable lesson in efficiency, forcing me to think about how to conserve every byte of space and CPU cycle. Anyhow, this limitation stemmed partly from the 6502 processor's unconventional memory structure. Rather than using a straightforward memory model, the 6502 had a small scratchpad and relied on special addressing modes to access different parts of memory. Its instruction set was even more peculiar than the 80X86, making it far better suited for lightweight assembly programming rather than handling more complex operating systems.

Another issue was the restricted execution stack, both in terms of size and where it could be placed. To get around this, a custom stack solution had to be implemented in software, further complicating development. Dealing with the restricted execution stack on the Apple II was one of the trickiest challenges. The stack was small and locked into a specific memory location, which made it hard to manage anything complex. I had to be extremely careful with function calls and recursion since the native stack just couldn't handle anything too deep or complex. In one case, I was trying to develop a simple recursive algorithm, and the system would crash every time because the stack would overflow. Wasn't fun.

What made the Apple II stand out in its time was the way it offloaded hardware functions, such as disk data encoding and head positioning, to software, keeping hardware costs down. However, this approach had its drawbacks, as it forced software to manage hardware in real-time, monopolizing the CPU for extended periods to handle these tasks. I remember one particular time when I was working on a disk utility for the Apple II where this was made abundently clear to me. The task involved managing disk data encoding and handling the drive‚Äôs head positioning, something that was usually managed by dedicated hardware in more modern machines. But on the Apple II, I had to write software to manage these low-level operations directly. This meant writing complex routines to handle the disk‚Äôs head movement and encoding the data correctly on the fly. It felt like I was working more on hardware-level code than application code at times. The downside, though, was that this approach meant the CPU was entirely consumed during these operations. I remember having to carefully schedule my software to avoid missing any crucial real-time tasks, like ensuring the disk didn‚Äôt lose data when switching between reading and writing.

As hardware has evolved and become more affordable, with smarter components handling functions independently, the Apple II‚Äôs method of shifting tasks to software has become less practical. While it did save on hardware costs, it complicated software development and limited the system's overall potential.¬®


Anyhoo, good memories.", 'The ARM1 processor was developed in just 18 months. Steve Furber defined the architecture while Sophie Wilson developed the instruction set. The first 32 bit Computer the Acorn was released in 1984. Look at ARM today', 'thank you for this mindblowing quality', 'I knew Steve and Waz and worked for one of the first computer stores in the country.  I sold a great many Apple I, Apple 2, Lisa, Mac, and IBM Personal Computer.', "I don't see viewer in this video üòÖ", 'I saw this video without knowing the title and the intro blew my mind, so well done', 'I was born in late 80s and I worked with these üôÇ', "Although I was born in the early 90's I got to use these in school and i'm so glad I got to", 'At least I keep my HDD but I threw out my free Macintosh Apple II some day will get back and setup my own Apple museum', 'The fact that it‚Äôs as old as me and still working üòÇme', 'Computers were well established by 1984, and many people had Apple IIs, TRS-80's or Ataris.  IBM PCs started to become popular in the 80's, but they were too expensive for home users until the BIOS was cloned by Phoenix and others and cheap clones became common.  Apple II and Atari computers were good for gaming, and there were a few business applications.  However, the Apple II and most early computers were only 8-bit, so very limited in memory and with only 40-column displays.  The IBM PC had a lot of RAM for the time (up to 640 Kb) and a high-resolution 80-column display.  Lotus 123 (spreadsheet) and WordPerfect (Word Processor) quickly became popular and it was a common business tool very quickly, although networking took a little longer.
I used the original Mac in 1984, and you had to swap disks constantly, so doing anything--even simple word processing, was a major pain.  It really wasn't really very useful, although the GUI environment was quite stunning.  You could print anything on screen, but printing was very slow and low-resolution.  When the "Fat Mac" '(512 Kb) came out, the disk swapping was reduced and hard disks made it better still, although early Mac hard disks very very slow and expensive.  Even so, the Mac didn't really become popular with business until the Apple LaserWriter was invented.  This created the desktop publishing business and made the Mac a unique and very useful business tool, although it never caught on generally with businesses because it was so expensive.  A Mac and LaserWriter cost almost as much as a car. 
By th late 80's, early versions of Windows were out, and there were other GUI computers like the Atari ST and Amiga that were cheaper than Macs (and had color screens).  Windows 3.1 around 1990 was comparable to Macs in many ways and really shifted the momentum of the undustry back to PCs and Windows.  Macs grew less popular and almost died off, before the iMac in the late 1990's made them popular again.
It's easy for current Mac users to get nostalgic about Macs, but for the 1980's and 90's, they were very much niche products and very expensive.  The turnaround of Apple into a popular and trendy home machine is really a post-2000 thing.', 'him: guess what color this is me: beige him:1980s brown', 'My first pc user experience was in 1992 (12yo), it was ZX Spectrum (Sinclair Research) at that time .', 'How are millennials so uniformed about old stuff üòÇ I‚Äôm gen z and I feel like I know so much more lmao', 'I love old computers, they did not spy on people', 'why is the mac more quiet than my ps4', 'Kid: why do I have to listen to you?

I was there and most of what these people are attributing to Apple had already been a small deal with CP/M (etc) computers and became a BIG deal with the 8088 based IBM PC in 8/81 and successors running DOS.  Apple, especially the Macintosh, showed up after that (1/84) and took a LONG time to have any significant effect.  The Mac was a lot more expensive, there was almost no software for it, and it didn't support aftermarket h/w cards.  It took a LONG time to become even slightly useful for most purposes that had already developed by then.  So the effect it had on computer culture was pretty slight for a very long time.  Apple added the "cute" factor with the Mac but the basic trajectory things were going in had been established long before that.  The mouse did became a thing because of the Mac but even that was literally just stolen from Xerox.  Man, I'm literally watching revisionist - or just plain inaccurate - history being made right here right now.  Jeez ...', 'Bill definitely had a few before his segment, man

I just want to make one quick correction to the brother talking about robotic process automation.  The crazy part about robotic process automation is it has nothing to do with physical robots.

Robotic process automation is meant to automate repetitive processes that people do with white collar jobs. Think data entry.  Let's say you have somebody that has to use a nine key to take data from one spreadsheet and import it into a piece of legacy software that is critical to the company.  You could replace the legacy software with a new system that could accept the spreadsheets directly , but that can cost tens of millions of dollars.  Instead you pay anywhere from 5 to 20 to 100 people depending on the size of the company $40,000 a year to do data entry.  Anybody that's ever worked at a bank, or an insurance company, or credit card processor knows exactly this kind of monotonous work.

What's something like RPA does is it would read the characters in the spreadsheet program and then simulate typing the correct characters into the data entry program.  This piece of software my only cost $50,000 or $100,000 to build, but it would allow you to continue using your legacy software that will cost ten million dollars to replace, and get rid of those data entry people.  So you might pay $100,000 once to replace people that you're playing anywhere from $200,000 to four million dollars every year.

Now I haven't seen this movie, but based on the video, it seems like the bad guy adopted the Wiggies? Danny calls them his daughters but they don't look biologically related.

Like imagine a movie about five girls who are adopted just to become "superstars" to make more money for a guy who's already rich, and who sabotages all their competition, even little kids. And he raises them to be scummy like him. Even threatens to not give them food if they don't behave as he says. For instance, in binary, 0.1 and 0.2 are repeating fractions, similar to how 1/3 is 0.333... in decimal. When these binary fractions are added together, the result is a value very close to 0.3, but not exactly 0.3.

Python (and most programming languages) tries to represent this as accurately as possible, leading to the small difference you see (0.30000000000000004).

This is a common issue with floating-point arithmetic in many programming languages.', 'Computers aren‚Äôt better then people, they are faster then people', 'Use java', 'The problem is not completely here but more in the binary representation of floating points, because it can yield infinite representation (e. g., the representation of 0.1).', '"I've always thought computers are better at math than humans..." Super rude of him to cut taking it off.', 'is the k552 and k552 kurama different?', '<3', "Big head's up if anyone is considering modding/cleaning one of these!!!!!

I just finished trying to clean and disassemble my Redragon K552..... 

However I followed this guide and turns out there's like multiple different versions of both the RGB, full RGB, and non RGB K552's the older ones being non hot-swappable and the newer ones are.


So after I got all my key caps off mine I tried to remove the switches thinking it was a hot-swap board and well...... I cracked one trying to pull it out (the switch works still) so I stopped and moved on too try and remove all the screws, turns out not only was my board really dirty, the screw layout was also different from the one in this video. So I fumbled around (broke my nice utility knife blade in half trying to pry the PCB/top case apart) only to discover I had missed 5 other screws hidden along the board between switches. 

After I realized that and got them removed I was finally able to remove the keyboard from the case, and sadly on mine I was not able to remove the metal plate or switches to clean it better because they are soldered on.

So I rinsed out the case and wiped down the top case with a Lysol wipe to clean it as best I could. Then dried the bottom case and reassembled the 2 and then filled a container with warm water and dish soap and put all the key caps in it to sit and clean them off.


And that's all just be aware that not all K552's will be the same unless you buy one from Amazon that's current if not and you get a used one make sure it's hot-swappable before buying it it'll make life way easier."]

Video Title: LG G2 vs. Samsung Galaxy S4 Smartphones Comparison Smackdown
Comment:
['I just got this phone in 2016! I frankly love it. The big deal about button placement is really not that big a deal folks! I like it because on my last phone, I tended to activate a button whenever I picked the phone up. The UI? really? You get used to it. Again, not a big deal. I wanted a Samsung phone initially but the price on a old LG G2 was cheaper so that is what I got. All of the criticism on plastic vs metal? Again, in the case of a mobile phone, nonsense. I picked up a few iphones and others with metal casings and really again not a big difference. Plastic is a bit "warmer" to the touch.', 'does lgg2 have gyroscope', "I had LG G2 Korean Version but Battery has only 2610mAh and the battery isn't good enough when i play the game can someone tell me can i replace my 
LG G2 korean version battery with the battery 3000mAh from US LG G2.", 'No HDMI on either ?  I will pass !', 'WTF..LG meaning Local Gadget.period!', 'If you get the Korean version of the LG G2 it has a removable battery with a removable battery and a sd card expansion slot.', 'This review was quiet biased. The Galaxy S4 i9500 is a bit better than the one you reviewed.', "From using both of these as daily drivers, I found the S4 to be better overall when everything is kept as it is, while I found the G2 better after rooting and modding. Problems with the unmodded G2 is that the oversized on-screen buttons and unadjusted UI scaling give you no benefit from having the larger screen. The S4 has more true screen real estate in practice. Shrinking or auto-hiding the on-screen buttons and lowering dpi solves this. S4 battery life is worse, but better when using a backup battery in external charger (= practically infinite battery life). The LG camera badly needs a mod that increases the shutter speed; out of the box it's extremely laggy, even if considerably sharper than the S4's and optically stabilized. Both have oppressive UI skins, but I found Samsung's to be slightly more feature rich. Modding in split screen dual app functionality tilts things in LG's favor, but it might be possible on the S4 too. Google Gemini and Google assistant are not to compare They are totally different. 
Google Gemini and Google Assistant are both AI assistants that can perform a variety of tasks, but they differ in their capabilities and intended use: 
 
Purpose:
Google Assistant is a voice assistant that helps with tasks like controlling your phone, making calls, and setting reminders. Gemini is a generative AI assistant that can answer unique questions, summarize documents, and plan trips. 
 
Features:
Gemini has advanced features like natural language understanding (NLU), which helps it understand the context of what you're saying. Gemini can also perform complex tasks like coding, idea generation, and image generation. 
 
Intended use:
Gemini is designed to be more personal and adapt to your interests and preferences. Google Assistant is designed for more communal use on shared devices, like smart home gadgets. 
 
Availability:
Gemini is the default assistant on the Pixel 9 family, but users can still choose to use Google Assistant. On Android devices, Gemini can perform some of the same tasks as Google Assistant, but some features may not be supported. Devices that don't support the Gemini mobile app, like watches and Smart Displays, will continue to use Google Assistant.", 'Gemini updated very well

Here's how the pun works:
"You are" is the setup for the comparison.
"fanta" is a brand of orange soda.
"orange" is the word that connects the two parts of the pun.
"a stick" is a visual representation of the word "orange" as a color.
So, the full sentence is: "You are Fanta orange (a stick)." This means that you are as orange as a stick.

From and To: Charge Cycles (This estimate includes avarage temperature from average charging and use)

Charging from 0 - 100% is 1 Cycle
Charging from 50 - 100% is .5 Cycle
Charging from 25 - 85% is .6 Cycle
Charging from 20 - 90% is .7 Cycle

(0% - 100%) 300 - 500 Cycles--------------100% of battery use lasting around 1 year
(50% - 100%) Around 1,000 Cycles------50% of battery use lasting around 2 years
(30% - 80%) Around 3,000 Cycles--------50% of battery use lasting around... (Phone breaks)
(25% - 85%) Around 2,500 Cycles--------60% of battery use lasting around... (Phone breaks) 
(20% - 90 %) Around 2,000 Cycles-------70% of battery use lasting around... (Phone breaks)

If your device offer disabling fast charging like on Galaxy devices, do it to keep cool.
If your device offer battery charge limit like on Galaxy Tab S4 at 85%, do it.
If you can install (Battery Charge Notifier) app on android, it will alarm when set charge limit is achieved. Alarm well sound every 30 seconds when charger is still connected until unplug.
Higher battery charge capacity remaining equals higher resale value.

Note: For accurate battery computer estimation, discharge your phone battery to 0% then charge to 100% uninterrupted ones a month.']

Anyway. their solution was for me to wipe clean the hard drive .. I was like, Hey.. No way! Why don't you just remove the personal items (pictures, documents, etc) I have on there.. I went home.. called Apple customer service.. I told them what happened. They suggested just wiping the computer clean and reinstalling Sierra.. But what about MY Stuff on it>>???

I said, Hey Apple messed up my computer.. why not repair it properly??? 

They made another appt with the Apple store.. I went in.. AGAIN.. Same story.. I left.. I went home and called Apple customer service.. Again.. this time spoke to a "Manager" for customer service.. Yep.. Same story. 

This was last Nov (2017).. it's now May 2018.. My computer has sat there in my drawer.. until I find a solution. 

BOTTOM LINE: I am super angry and disappointed with Apple. It was their software that messed my computer up .. and they are not taking responsibility for it..

Regarding the governments ability to impose "Reasonable Restraint" which has now become the mantra of our liberal influenced government.  
Supporters of the bill of rights claim they have a constitutional or Second Amendment right to keep and bear arms. Opponents counter even if it were the case, the government was granted the general power to place restraints on the right. Both of these assertions are based on a misconception concerning the intent of the document known as the Bill of Rights. 

When the Bill of Rights was submitted to the individual States for ratification, it was prefaced with a preamble. As stated in the preamble, the purpose of the Amendments was to prevent the government from ‚Äúmisconstruing or abusing its powers.‚Äù To accomplish this, ‚Äúfurther declaratory and restrictive clauses‚Äù were being recommended. The Amendments, when adopted, did not create any so-called constitutional rights or grant the government any power over individual rights; they placed additional restraints and qualifications on the powers of the  government concerning the rights enumerated in the Amendments.

By advancing the myth Amendments grant the American people their individual rights, the government has illegally converted enumerated restraints and qualifications on its power into legislative, executive, judicial and administrative power over individual rights. The government claims it was granted the constitutional authority to determine the extent of the individual rights enumerated in the Amendments and/or impose ‚Äúreasonable restraints‚Äù on those rights. This assertion is absurd. The government does not have the constitutional authority to ignore, circumvent, modify, negate or remove constitutional restraints placed on its power by the Amendments or convert them into a power over the individual right enumerated in the particular restraint.

A denial of power or an enumerated restraint on the exercise of power is not subject to interpretation or modification by the entity the restraint is being imposed upon. The restraints imposed by the Amendments, which were adopted 4 years after the Constitution was ratified, override the legislative, executive, judicial or administrative powers of the  government. If this were not the case, then the restraints would be meaningless because the  government could simply circumvent, modify or remove them. Why would the States have requested and adopted enumerated restraints on government power, subsequent to their ratification of the Constitution, if the  government possessed the authority to nullify them?

When the government infringes on one of the rights enumerated in the Bill of Rights it is not violating anyone‚Äôs constitutional rights; it is violating the additional restraint or qualification placed on its power by the particular Amendment where the right is enumerated. The distinction between rights and restraints is critical.  [The right is not given by the  Government.  Our rights are given by God and are inalienable.  Therefore, they can't be limited or taken away.]

As stated in the Declaration of Independence, the American people have unalienable rights that come from a higher source than government or a written document. By acknowledging people have natural rights, which are bestowed by a creator, the Founders laid the foundation for the principle the government does not have the lawful authority to take away or infringe on those rights. This principle was incorporated into the preamble and structure of the Amendments to secure individual rights from government encroachment; that is why they were designed and imposed as restraints on the exercise of power.

If the individual rights of the people had been created by the Constitution or an amendment to the document, then they would cease to be unalienable because the right would depend on the existence of a document. If the document or a provision of the document disappeared, so would the right. The belief individual rights were created by a written document has opened the door for the government to claim the power to define the extent of any right enumerated in an Amendment. This has transformed constitutional restraints placed on governmental power into subjective determinations of individual rights by the institutions of government. By failing to understand the difference between amendments that create rights and amendments that impose restraints on government, the American people are watching their individual rights vanish as they are reduced to the status of privileges bestowed by government because the constitutional restraints placed on governmental power are being replaced by government decree.

Opponents of the Amendments always try to diminish the right enumerated in the Amendments by asserting rights are not absolute. This is just another straw man argument because the Amendment is about imposing a restraint of the powers of the  government concerning a right: not granting a right or defining the extent of a right. In addition, a review of the Second Amendment shows the restraint imposed by the Amendment does not contain any exceptions.

Legal precedence supporting constitution and bill of rights. 

Marbury v. Madison, 5 US 137: ‚ÄúThe Constitution of these United States is the supreme law of the land. Any law that is repugnant to the Constitution is null and void of law.‚Äù

Murdock v. Penn., 319 US 105: ‚ÄúNo state shall convert a liberty into a privilege, license it, and attach a fee to it.‚Äù

Shuttlesworth v. Birmingham, 373 US 262: ‚ÄúIf the state converts a liberty into a privilege, the citizen can engage in the right with impunity.‚Äù

Owen v. Independence, 100 S.C.T. 1398, 445 US 622: ‚ÄúOfficers of the court have no immunity, when violating a Constitutional right, from liability. For they are deemed to know the law.‚Äù

Scheuer v. Rhodes, 416 U.S. 232, 1974: Expounds upon Owen Byers v. U.S., 273 U.S. 28 Unlawful search and seizure. Your rights must be interpreted in favor of the citizen.

Boyd v. U.S., 116 U.S. 616: ‚ÄúThe court is to protect against any encroachment of Constitutionally secured liberties.‚Äù

Miranda v. Arizona, 384 U.S. 436: ‚ÄúWhere rights secured (Affirmed) by the Constitution are involved, there can be no rule making or legislation, which would abrogate them.‚Äù

I would like to know it the failures could involve X-Fives too.', 'Read through the lawsuit, thanks for linking it. My personal theory is that - while statistically almost certainly some of these documented reports are unintentional finger-on-trigger pulls - the prevalence of their occurrence with this particular firearm indicates something about the design, or the manufacturing of the design, disproportionately lends the weapon to be unintentionally discharged - even while holstered. All of the reports are of the weapon being fired while in gentle motion/twisting/bending/holstering/belting etc. I wonder if the lack of an interior trigger safety (allowing the trigger to be pulled or hinged from any point) combined with the width of the trigger reduces the tolerance in safe holster design around the trigger guard. I wish we had better documentation of the specific holsters being used for each of these incidents. It could be that because of this reduced tolerance, leather, or unrigid or misshaped kydex, may cause the holster itself to be pulling the trigger, creating an obstruction that bows into the trigger guard enough to pull it and fire. 

The vast majority of these incidents involve issued carriers in some official capacity, not members of the general public. While I'm unaware of what percentage of P320s are issued vs purchased by regular consumers, the different choices in holsters between the public and professionals - which financial incentives may be more likely to push cheap, damaged, worn, improper, etc. holsters on - could be the cause for this discrepancy. It could also be the case that this low tolerance combined with the polymer frame allows for bending of the firearm/triggerguard itself and could work to put the trigger into harm's way by bowing the triggerguard out of the way or the trigger towards the edges of the holster. The lack of tolerance also makes the P320 more dangerous when something *does* inadvertently end up in the holster. A casing, a twig, a piece of fingernail, etc. These are all much more likely to defeat the P320s trigger than a trigger with a trigger safety.

I think that the P320s trigger design, when combined with a low quality or ill suited holster, or a dangerous but statistically ultimately inevitable foreign object winding up inside the holster are the cause for this one firearm spawning so many incidents of unintentional discharges.

At least one report involved a CAT scan and analysis of a weapon that fired while fully holstered and currently worn, supported by video evidence, identified manufacturing and design failures that contributed to the firing. *"crossed sear springs that apply upward spring pressure to the sear to keep it from releasing the striker." (section 108. Page 18) which is compelling, but I don't know enough about P320 or striker pistol design to really weigh in on it. If legit, it's possible that similar failures are responsible for many of these incidents involving fully holstered weapons firing - I think it's safe to assume that some fair percentage of discharges during holstering/reholstering were inadvertently and unawaredly caused by finger-on-trigger contact.

Sig's language of "voluntary upgrade", their insistence that any handgun could fire if "vibrated", their stated following of U.S. regulations that they were aware categorically do not exist and thus could not have been followed, their rewording of their manuals in the face of controversy, and the outsourcing of their manufacturing leaves me with doubts as to exactly how safe the firearm may be independent of user error. Clearly, the lack of civilian incidents indicates that many P320s are fully capable of being carried daily in quality holsters by responsible owners without incident. But, I have a hard time believing that fingers-on-triggers are causing 100% of these incidents as some allege. I think the design could have been made safer to minimize these incidents, and Sig bears some responsibility for not making those design decisions. A manual safety on more models, a safer more-tolerant trigger design, better manufacturing QC, better stress testing could have caught many of these issues ahead of time, including the drop-safe problem. Sig can make a quality firearm, but everyone has a few lemons, and I think the 320 as manufactured real-world is unnecessarily dangerous relative to its peers.', 'If you notice there‚Äôs professionals, working a job where an accidental discharge on their part could result in termination or  disciplinary action.
